docs.abstract: The Missouri senator is in a neck-and-neck race to keep a crucial seat in Democratic hands, facing criticism from her opponent that she’s a Washington insider.
docs.snippet: The Missouri senator is in a neck-and-neck race to keep a crucial seat in Democratic hands, facing criticism from her opponent that she’s a Washington insider.
docs.lead_paragraph: PORTAGEVILLE, Mo. — Senator Claire McCaskill had rolled through miles of cotton and soybean fields, heading deep into enemy territory — Missouri’s Bootheel, Trump Country.

headline.main: Claire McCaskill Is in a Rugged Political Fight. She’s Survived Them Before.
headline.print_headline: In Missouri Race, McCaskill Says, ‘Everything Has to Go Well’

docs.abstract: She’s a 27-year-old refugee from Afghanistan who won an upset victory in a New Hampshire state house primary. “There can be change, yes. Why not?” said Safiya Wazir.
docs.snippet: She’s a 27-year-old refugee from Afghanistan who won an upset victory in a New Hampshire state house primary. “There can be change, yes. Why not?” said Safiya Wazir.
docs.lead_paragraph: It was a mere state house race, below the radar, with fewer than 500 votes cast. But Safiya Wazir’s upset victory in New Hampshire on Sept. 11 is yet one more striking example of how nontraditional candidates are upending expectations in this extraordinary election season.

headline.main: She Was a Refugee From Afghanistan. She May Soon Enter the New Hampshire Legislature.

docs.abstract: The president and the healthy economy have become countervailing forces, with his self-inflicted wounds obscuring the Republican message, and buoying Democrats
docs.snippet: The president and the healthy economy have become countervailing forces, with his self-inflicted wounds obscuring the Republican message, and buoying Democrats
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As Democrats enter the fall midterm campaign with palpable confidence about reclaiming the House and perhaps even the Senate, tensions are rising between the White House and congressional Republicans over who is to blame for political difficulties facing the party, with President Trump’s advisers pointing to the high number of G.O.P. retirements and lawmakers placing the blame squarely on the president’s divisive style.

headline.main: The Economy Is Humming, but Trump Is Tweeting. Republicans Are Worried.
headline.print_headline: Chaos May Offset  Economy’s Surge,  Costing the G.O.P.

byline.original: By Jonathan Martin and Alexander Burns

docs.abstract: Trump voters can have long memories. Democratic voters in New Jersey have not fully forgiven Senator Robert Menendez. And other points from the night’s primaries.
docs.snippet: Trump voters can have long memories. Democratic voters in New Jersey have not fully forgiven Senator Robert Menendez. And other points from the night’s primaries.
docs.lead_paragraph: The battle for control of Congress was front and center on Tuesday night, with races taking shape in several intensely contested House seats in California and New Jersey. But there were revealing elections in the Midwest and the South, too, underscoring President Trump’s power in the Republican Party and the different ways Democrats hope to loosen his hold on red-state America.

byline.original: By Alexander Burns, Nick Corasaniti, Jonathan Martin and Matt Flegenheimer

docs.abstract: With Republicans confident about holding onto their Senate majority, the party is fortifying defenses in conservative-leaning districts that were considered secure but now may be at risk.
docs.snippet: With Republicans confident about holding onto their Senate majority, the party is fortifying defenses in conservative-leaning districts that were considered secure but now may be at risk.
docs.lead_paragraph: CINCINNATI — As the 2018 midterm campaign enters its final full week, House Republicans are rushing to fortify their defenses in conservative-leaning districts they thought were secure, pouring millions of dollars into a last-minute bid to build a new firewall against Democrats.

headline.main: Republicans Rushing to Save House Seats From Onslaught of Democratic Money
headline.print_headline: House Republicans on Edge as Democrats Rake In Cash for Close Races
